{"name": "Anthony Wood", "link": "https://www.facebook.com/anthony.wood1?hc_ref=ARSKPb2rxKwhQ5_hjDSuXQI5Ht7rnucHQv5k_EAsNmzsqIpuxvI8OurlKjUb0fBbMFA&fref=nf", "comment": "<p>Hi. We currently moved into a new place and have no power. Your company said it should be hooked up between 8am and midnight yesterday. But nothing has happened. Your offices aren't open on the weekend. Does this mean we have to be stuck with no power until Tuesday?</p>", "timestamp": "10 June 2016"}
{"name": "Thorsten Zeke", "link": "https://www.facebook.com/EnergyAustralia/?fref=nf", "comment": "<p>Not happy<br> Got an \"estimation\" gas bill, which has charged me MORE than average than other bills <br> I have NO DOGS, or gates in the way, and never had an \"estimated\" bill before <br> Maybe get your meter readers to take the time to look for the actual meter instead of taking the easy way out to estimate a reading. <br> Even knock on the door to ask where it is</p>", "timestamp": "10 June 2016"}
{"name": "Sylvia Else", "link": "https://www.facebook.com/EnergyAustralia/?fref=nf", "comment": "<p>I've received an bill based on an estimated reading. OK, so stuff happens, but estimating that my entire usage occured during peak time when I was on a time of use tarrif seems just dishonest. Yes, I know that in the normal way of things, the total amount paid gets corrected at the next meter reading, but nothing undoes the fact that you get an interest free loan of the overpaid amount.</p>", "timestamp": "9 June 2016"}
